{
  "doc_id": "37540",
  "text": "In a deep mutational scan, a library of protein variants is first introduced into a model system [CITATION_1] . Model systems that have been used in deep mutational scanning include phage, bacteria, yeast, and cultured mammalian cells. A selection is applied for protein function or another molecular property of interest, altering the frequency of each variant according to its functional capacity. Selections can be growth-based or implement physical separation of variants into bins, as in phage display or flow sorting of cells. Next, the frequency of each variant in each time point or bin is determined by using deep sequencing to count the number of times each variant appears. Here, the variable region is either directly sequenced using a single-end or paired-end strategy, or a short barcode that uniquely identifies each variant in the population is sequenced instead [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Barcoding enables accurate assessment of variable regions longer than a single sequencing read [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Analysis of the change in each variant's frequency throughout the selection yields a score that estimates the variant's effect. Scoring the performance of individual variants is distinct from a related class of methods that quantify tolerance for change at each position in a target protein [CITATION_7] . Those approaches enable a different set of biological inferences that we do not seek to address here. Guidelines for the design of deep mutational scanning experiments have been discussed elsewhere [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] .",
